Process for obtaining verification data:

1.  Run layout

The sim runs are cataloged into different run-sets.  Each set represents a
different environment setting.  Within each set there are a number of runs,
with each representing a different duration over which the initial
propagation is to run; these are named RUN_verif_<n> where <n> represents the
duration.

In the SET_forward_* sets, there is also a RUN_baseline, which provides data
from a regular Trick-managed integration over 6000 seconds.


2. Execute the runs

Run:
   bash run_all.sh

Execute all runs for the set(s) of interest.

The SET_reverse_* sets back-propagate the initial state using this model, then
forward-propagate that state using a regular Trick-managed integration
mechanism for the same duration.  The data of interest is the final state,
which should be close to the originally specified state.

The SET_forward_* sets forward-propagate the initial state using this model and
immediately stop.  The data of interest is this final state which can then be
compared against a regular forward-propagating Trick-managed integration over
the same duration.  Note that in these runs the jeod time is "moved forward" by
the amount of propagation_time, so that the pfix frames align at t=0 between
RUN_verif* and RUN_baseline/

See SIM_initial_propagation_visual.png in this directory for a visualization
of this explanation


3.  Post-process the data

Execute the script "post_process_data":
   bash post_process_data   # Gather data into SET*/RUN_combined/

The post_process_data script extracts the data from all of the different runs
for a single comparison.  For all sets, a new "run", RUN_combined, is created
by this script.  Within RUN_combined, a new data-set will be created containing
the data of interest from each of the set's runs.  Data from RUN_combined
can then be used as a measure of the effect of propagating within a certain
environment over a variable propagation-duration.

For the SET_reverse_* sets, the last recorded data-set is simply extracted from
each respective run.  Each run's last recorded data-set represents a state that
should be back at the original state.  it is the state of the vehicle after
having gone through a reverse propagation and subsequent forward integration
through a time period equal to the timestamp of that last recorded data set.
The combined data set can be compared against the initially-specified state
to evaluate the error induced by the reverse propagation as a function of the
duration of said propagation.

For the SET_forward_* sets, the only recorded data is that of the initially-
propagated state, recorded at t=0 and representative of the state at
t=propagation-duration. The timestamp (t=0) is overwritten by the value of the
propagation duration, creating a set of data points much like a set generated
from a regular Trick-managed sim.  This data set can then be compared against
the RUN_baseline output to measure how the the two propagation methods diverge
over time.


4. Analyze the Data

For SET_forward*/, the data comparisons of the combined data against the
baseline data are launched automatically by the post-processing script.
The differences are plotted and can be compared against the plots committed
for verification purposes.

For SET_reverse*/ each RUN_combined/log_test_data.csv is self-verifying, meaning
the values should be close to the initial conditions. You can view all runs
together easily via:

   trick-qp SET_reverse_*/RUN_combined
   <hit comparison plot button>
